A piece of gold has a mass of $760$ grams and a volume of $40 \text{ cm}^3$.

\vspace{0.5cm} 

\qquad Work out the density of the piece of gold.

\vspace{8cm} 

\hfill \makebox[4cm]{\dotfill}

$a$ is directly proportional to $b$.

\vspace{0.5cm} 

\qquad When $a = 5$, $b = 20$.

\vspace{0.5cm} 

\qquad Find the value of $b$ when $a = 7$.

\vspace{8cm}

\hfill $b$ =\makebox[4cm]{\dotfill}

\noindent\quad Here is a polygon.
\vspace{0.5cm}
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
        \draw (90:1.5) -- (162:1.5) -- (234:1.5) -- (306:1.5) -- (18:1.5) -- cycle;
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

(a) Write down the mathematical name of this polygon. \\[2cm] % Adjust spacing as needed

\hfill \makebox[5cm]{\dotfill}
\vspace{0.2cm}

\noindent Here is a prism.
\vspace{0.5cm}
\begin{center}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Front pentagon
        \coordinate (A) at (90:1.5);
        \coordinate (B) at (162:1.5);
        \coordinate (C) at (234:1.5);
        \coordinate (D) at (306:1.5);
        \coordinate (E) at (18:1.5);
        % Shifted back pentagon
        \coordinate (F) at ($(A)+(1,1)$);
        \coordinate (G) at ($(B)+(1,1)$);
        \coordinate (H) at ($(C)+(1,1)$);
        \coordinate (I) at ($(D)+(1,1)$);
        \coordinate (J) at ($(E)+(1,1)$);
        % Draw front pentagon
        \draw (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle;
        % Draw back pentagon (dashed for hidden edges)
        \draw[dashed] (F) -- (G) -- (H) -- (I) -- (J) -- cycle;
        % Connect front and back pentagons
        \draw (A) -- (F);
        \draw (B) -- (G);
        \draw (C) -- (H);
        \draw (D) -- (I);
        \draw (E) -- (J);
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}
\noindent Each edge of the prism has a length of 7.5 cm.
\vspace{0.3cm}

(b) Work out the total perimeter of the prism.

\vspace{5cm}

